Problem Statement
In a distant galaxy, an interplanetary communication network is built using relay towers. The network forms a binary tree, where each tower can communicate with at most two child towers.

Every tower is assigned a signal strength value.

A tower is called a Peak Relay if its signal strength is strictly greater than the signal strength of every tower in its subtree, excluding itself.

In other words, for a tower to be considered a Peak Relay, no descendant of that tower may have a signal strength greater than or equal to its own.

Leaf towers (towers with no descendants) are always considered Peak Relays.

Given the structure of the communication network, determine the total number of Peak Relay towers.


Illustration
 
          50
         /  \
       20    30
      / \    /
    10  15 25
 
Tower 50 is a Peak Relay because it is greater than all of its descendants: 20, 30, 10, 15, 25.
Tower 20 is a Peak Relay because it is greater than 10 and 15.
Tower 30 is a Peak Relay because it is greater than 25.
Towers 10, 15, and 25 have no descendants and are therefore Peak Relays.
Hence, the total number of Peak Relay towers is 6.

Input Format
The first line contains a single integer N, representing the number of towers.
The next N lines describe the towers.
The i-th of these lines contains three integers: SignalStrength LeftChild RightChild
where:

SignalStrength is the signal strength of tower i.
LeftChild is the index of the left child of tower i.
RightChild is the index of the right child of tower i.
A value of -1 indicates that the corresponding child does not exist.
The towers are indexed from 0 to N − 1, and tower 0 is the root of the communication network.

Output Format
Print a single integer representing the number of Peak Relay towers in the network.

Constraints
1 ≤ N ≤ 10000

1 ≤ SignalStrength ≤ 10^9

Sample Testcase 0
Testcase Input
6
50 1 2
20 3 4
30 5 -1
10 -1 -1
15 -1 -1
25 -1 -1
Testcase Output
6
Explanation
           50
         /      \
       20       30
      /   \       /
    10  15  25



Tower 50 is a Peak Relay because its signal strength is greater than all of its descendants (20, 30, 10, 15, 25).


Tower 20 is a Peak Relay because it is greater than both 10 and 15.


Tower 30 is a Peak Relay because it is greater than 25.


Towers 10, 15, and 25 are leaf towers and are therefore Peak Relays.


Hence, the total number of Peak Relay towers is 6.

Sample Testcase 1
Testcase Input
5
20 1 2
25 3 4
10 -1 -1
5 -1 -1
7 -1 -1
Testcase Output
4
Explanation
      20
       /    \
     25    10
    /  \
   5    7



Tower 20 is not a Peak Relay because its descendant 25 has a greater signal strength.


Tower 25 is a Peak Relay because it is greater than both of its descendants (5 and 7).


Towers 10, 5, and 7 are leaf towers and are therefore Peak Relays.


Hence, the total number of Peak Relay towers is 4.
